!URxvt key map
!
! This is used in conjunction with screen to control its behavior.
! The default command character for screen is C-a(control-a), which is
! also used by emacs. I redefined the command character to C-~(octal
! 036, using the escape command). Here, we generate this control
! sequence using Mod4-a(windows-a). and Mod4 with q/w/e/r generates
! C-~ 0/1/2/3, which will be interpreted by screen as switching to the
! 1st/2nd/3rd/4th window.
URxvt.keysym.Mod4-a: \035
URxvt.keysym.Mod4-q: \0350
URxvt.keysym.Mod4-w: \0351
URxvt.keysym.Mod4-e: \0352
URxvt.keysym.Mod4-r: \0353
! additional control to manipulate windows in screen
URxvt.keysym.Mod4-Left: \035p
URxvt.keysym.Mod4-Right: \035n
URxvt.keysym.Mod4-S-Down: \035c
! For use with HappyHacking, the left/right arrow keys on HappyHacking
! are generated by Fn+semicolon/apostrophe. By doing these mappings I
! don't need to hold Fn.
URxvt.keysym.Mod4-semicolon: \035p
URxvt.keysym.Mod4-apostrophe: \035n
URxvt.keysym.Mod4-slash: \035c

